“When I was 12, I had a motorbike. I’ve had one since I was 12 because that’s what everybody had. But the police were completely powerless. They just had to shrug their shoulders and say ‘that’s how it is’.

“In my time, we didn’t have the one year Nairobi Trade Licence; the registration was free,” Mr Pericles said.

Speaking yesterday afternoon at the presentation of 20 motorbikes to the Royal Solomon Islands Police Force (RSIPF) by Bougainville Regional Security Coordinator Ziggy Steiner, Minister for Police and Fire Services Bryan Kramer urged the RSIPF to use the donations from Coca-Cola at pool cricketers during the surf and turf Octepuss match over Miyarai Island in 2016, among others.

He revealed in 2015 that 64 people died and many more at the island of Guadalcanal from motorbike accidents, due to irresponsible riding and irresponsible riding habits.

Minister Kramer said motorbike riders need to have their license renewed periodically, insurance taken out for the bikes, and a license acceptance procedure, especially for commercial drivers.

He said he has been working on a draft legislation to be presented in Parliament by July this year.
